    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nRight now the only way to create floating windows is via the API. This prevents quick, ad-hoc use in user commands/bindings/etc and means there's loads of plugins that all (re)implement essentially identical functionality even for the most rudimentary 'open a floating terminal' cases.\n\nIt also means incrementally enhancing VimL scripts/plugins to use floats using `has('nvim')` is more challenging, as calling neovim APIs from VimL is possible but unwieldy and not nearly as intuitive.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI propose a `:floating` command modifier, that similar to `:horizontal`, `:vertical`, `:tab` etc. affects how the command opens windows. The configuration for windows created by `:floating` is taken from the `'floatopts'` option, which is a `key:val,key:val` style option that mirrors `vim.api.keyset.win_config`.\n\nUnresolved Questions:\n- scoping of `'floatopts'`. tab-page local makes obvious sense, but maybe also window or buffer-local, such that `:floating split #n` can be flexible?\n- behaviour when multiple windows are opened like this (I haven't tested how Neovim handles overlapping floats in different scenarios)",
